'''Koka''' (可口; Kěkǒu) is brand of [[instant noodle]], manufactured by Tat Hui Foods Pte. Ltd. - a company founded in [[Singapore]] in 1986. The noodles are available in a variety of flavours, as packets or [[cup noodles]]. They are sold within Singapore, and since 1987 have been exported to markets in Europe, America, Australia and India.<ref name=about>{{cite web|url=http://www.tathui.com/abt.php|title=About Us|work=tathui.com|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209214926/http://tathui.com/abt.php|archivedate=9 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Along with the Sanwa noodle brand, Tat Hui exports over 100 million packets a year,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5cSIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA164#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=164|title=Invisible Gold in Asia: Creating Wealth Through Intellectual Property|author= David Llewely|publisher=Marshall Cavendish International|date= 28 February 2011}}</ref> and are a leading brand in Ireland, behind Unilever's [[Pot Noodle]], where they are distributed by Boyne Valley Foods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromonitor.com/noodles-in-ireland/report|title=Noodles in Ireland|work=euromonitor.com}}</ref>

==Manufacturing==
Koka's products are manufactured and packaged in Tat Hui's factory in [[Jurong]], Singapore. Their noodles are air-dried rather than deep-fried in the usual Asian manner.

==Products==
Koka products include instant noodles available in packets, cups and bowls. In 2015, they introduced [http://www.kokanoodles.com/our-family/koka-cream-soup Koka Creamy Soup], the first of its kind with an East-West fusion of creamy soup with a surprise chunk of crushed, springy noodles. Their flavours sold include [[Laksa]] Singapura, [[Black_pepper_crab|Black Pepper]] fried noodles, and [[Tom_yum|Tom Yum]] noodles. Koka also offer a [[gluten-free]] range, [http://www.kokanoodles.com/our-family/koka-silk Koka Silk].

